INSERT INTO "scraper_summitpost_climber_log" VALUES (2,'247651','','/devil-s-golf-ball/247651','/devil-s-golf-ball/climbers-log/247651/d-146721#146721','Nov 10, 2012','Hardest Bolt Ladder I\'ve Done','Success!','I\'ve gotten quite proficient at the LeConte Boulder bolt ladder, and the Kor Roof on the S Face of Washington Column was easy. These 6 bolts kicked my butt! Definitely be ready to use your aiders in pairs on this one. Also, my short reach forced me to snag a shallow finger pocket to stay upright in the top step just barely long enough to clip the last bolt.',NULL),(3,'150794','via north route of peak 12,048','/mount-tukuhnikivatz/150794','/mount-tukuhnikivatz/climbers-log/150794/d-6128#6128','June 11, 2003','Route Climbed: via north route of peak 12,048','No','Great route, the sliver of snow along the ridgeline was a welcome reprieve from the killer talus and scree. It was the first named peak (2nd total) of a ridgerun that day covering 6 peaks, which included Tuk, Peale, and Mellenthin.',NULL),(4,'151412','CMC','/mount-moran/151412','/mount-moran/climbers-log/151412/d-6138#6138','August, 2002','Route Climbed: CMC Date Climbed: August, 2002','No','Beautiful mountain.  I kayaked across Leigh Lake and scrambled up the wash below the hanging glacier below the CMC.  Definitely the most scenic campsite I\'ve ever had. It\'s too bad my climbing partners\' incessant tobacco and marijuana smoking made me too sick to continue the next day.  I\'ll definitely have to head back to finish this great climb!',NULL),(5,'153693','East Ridge from Basin Mountain, traversed to Four Gables','/south-basin-peak-pt-13-240/153693','/south-basin-peak-pt-13-240/climbers-log/153693/d-18851#18851','Aug 3, 2004','East Ridge from Basin Mountain, traversed to ','Success!','The east ridge had some really fun class 4 scrambling. This is an excellent peak to do in combo with Basin Mountain!',NULL),(6,'650446','','/mount-florence/650446','/mount-florence/climbers-log/650446/d-121725#121725','Aug 4, 2006','Forgot about this one','Success!','until I read my other summit registers!',NULL),(7,'151893','','/simmons-peak/151893','/simmons-peak/climbers-log/151893/d-41961#41961','Aug 4, 2006','Sierra Challenge 2006 - Climbed SW Slope','Success!','Finishing the grand tour of Vogelsang Pk and Mt Florence, I bagged Simmons on my way to Parson\'s Pass. I would have also climbed Parson\'s Peak if a thunderstorm hadn\'t developed.',NULL),(8,'150530','SW Ridge via Collier Glacier','/north-sister/150530','/north-sister/climbers-log/150530/d-27228#27228','September 5th, 2005','Route Climbed: SW Ridge via Collier Glacier D','Success!','A beautiful climb, although the route done w/o snow leaves something to be desired - I pray to god I never get on rock that loose ever again! It was interesting watching breezes set off rockfall on the Terrible Traverse. The Bowling Alley was actually really fun, with relatively solid rock (which got more solid as the scrambling got more difficult).',NULL),(9,'406145','','/mt-carl-heller/406145','/mt-carl-heller/climbers-log/406145/d-120759#120759','Mar 14, 2011','Scary but Memorable Winter Climb','Success!','Climbed the East Ridge via George Creek with Vitaliy Musiyenko, Shane Rathbun, Kevin Trieu, and Maxim Belyakov. Bivvied at the top of the snow couloir after 16 hrs of climbing and summitted the next day. The hike out was very long!',NULL),(10,'150440','','/mount-humphreys/150440','/mount-humphreys/climbers-log/150440/d-119810#119810','Feb 13, 2011','Full East Arete in Winter','Success!','Vitaliy and I started at the saddle between Magic McGee &amp; the 13,000 ft subpeak and climbed the entire ridge. Boots &amp; packs made it more fun. So did the snow cave bivy from 100\' below the summit plateau.',NULL),(11,'150526','','/mount-starr-king/150526','/mount-starr-king/climbers-log/150526/d-113821#113821','Oct 9, 2010','via NE Face (not Bob\'s route?)','Success!','Dayhiked from Happy Isles with Vitaliy, Max, &amp; Blazin. Followed N Ridge from Panorama Trail junction over Pt. 8,574 (horrendous bushwacking!).',NULL),(12,'528220','','/mount-morgenson-0-5-mi-w-of-mt-russell/528220','/mount-morgenson-0-5-mi-w-of-mt-russell/climbers-log/528220/d-113383#113383','Aug 15, 2010','Nice to tag','Success!','Staying closer to the North Ridge provides one with less loose rock and the occasional cl. 3 scramble. A nice dayhike on the last day of the 2010 Sierra Challenge!',NULL),(13,'154659','','/mount-robinson/154659','/mount-robinson/climbers-log/154659/d-108258#108258','Jul 17, 2010','W Ridge','Success!','Climbed the peak via the West Ridge with Vitaliy. Careful routfinding kept the route at cl. 3 to cl.4-? Incredible exposure, and great scrambling! I couldn\'t tell which summit was the highest and couldn\'t locate the register, so I climbed the three obviously highest summits.',NULL),(14,'150378','','/half-dome/150378','/half-dome/climbers-log/150378/d-113376#113376','Oct 2, 2010','Electrifying Cables Descent','Success!','Via Snake Dike with friends Daniel Honegger (my rope), Mike Shen , &amp; Edward Lau. My friends were sport climbers, so Dan and I left my trad gear in for Mike &amp; Ed to clip through for the first 2 pitches, then we climbed as completely separate teams for the rest. A great climb!',NULL),(15,'150613','','/north-peak/150613','/north-peak/climbers-log/150613/d-14553#14553','Sep 25, 2010','Ice is nice!','Success!','September 25th, 2010 - (Right) North Couloir',NULL),(16,'150527','','/mount-clark/150527','/mount-clark/climbers-log/150527/d-112691#112691','Sep 18, 2010','Loooong Dayhike','Success!','Dayhiked via NW Arete from Happy Isles TH with Joel Wilson and Heyning Cheng. I carried a rope and rack to lead the exposed sections for the others, and it came in handy! I started on the 4th class crack, but found two sections that I\'d say were 5.4-5.5 (so \'classic\' Sierra cl. 4?). We avoided the bushwack hell on the way up but couldn\'t avoid it on the way down.',NULL),(17,'153127','Men at Work','/pothole-dome/153127','/pothole-dome/climbers-log/153127/d-18484#18484','October 12, 2003, July 3rd (with mommy!)','Route Climbed: Men at Work Date Climbed: Octo','Success!','September 6, 2010 - TRed the right N Side, descended Men at Work after cleaning the top-ropes.',NULL),(18,'151086','','/crystal-crag/151086','/crystal-crag/climbers-log/151086/d-112381#112381','Sep 11, 2010','In the Area','Success!','so I couldn\'t pass off ticking off one of the routes listed in Croft\'s guidebook :-). Led the first and third pitch of the N Arete &amp; simul-climbed to the summit. Descended the S Ridge, taking a difficult line (cl. 4-5). Then I realized I left my sneakers on the summit, so I climbed up and down an easier line (cl. 3).',NULL),(19,'647234','','/puppy-dome/647234','/puppy-dome/climbers-log/647234/d-112380#112380','Sep 12, 2010','Puppy Crack, and two lines off the summit','Success!','Led puppy crack, then set up a TR on the left and right cracks leading to the summit. The left crack is a nice 5.6 climb, good protection for leading, and the initial slab isn\'t too runout or difficult. The right crack is easier than it looks (5.3?), but if you climb the lower slab direct, rather than using the cheater log propped up, then I\'d say it was a 5.10a/b and there is only scarce and questionable pro at the upper half.',NULL),(20,'151389','','/lembert-dome/151389','/lembert-dome/climbers-log/151389/d-18485#18485','Sep 12, 2010','2X','Success!','September 12th, 2010 - Climbed NW Books - Descended S Slopes - A nice easy trad lead.',NULL),(21,'150516','','/matthes-crest/150516','/matthes-crest/climbers-log/150516/d-111928#111928','Sep 4, 2010','Wonderful Climb!','Success!','Led two pitches to the crest, and simul-climbed to the North Summit at about the same speed as some of the other soloists. The 5.7 knob/crack pitch was a bit much with a heavy pack on so I had to ditch it at the notch to finish the pitch - stout!',NULL),(22,'150524','','/cathedral-peak/150524','/cathedral-peak/climbers-log/150524/d-111280#111280','Aug 28, 2010','Cold and Windy','Success!','Despite the winds and occasional snow/hail flurries, the weather stayed just good enough for us to finish the SE Buttress. Fun route! The chimney was quite the pain in the butt with a pack on, though, but good practice leading offwidth as well!',NULL),(23,'150612','','/bear-creek-spire/150612','/bear-creek-spire/climbers-log/150612/d-110781#110781','Aug 22, 2010','NE Ridge Simul-Climb','Success!','High winds left me and Gordon Ye uncertain about climbing the route, but luckily the winds had eased off by the time we started the route. A great climb, and next time I\'ll be back for the North Ridge.',NULL),(24,'151351','','/pyramid-peak-little-lakes-valley/151351','/pyramid-peak-little-lakes-valley/climbers-log/151351/d-110779#110779','Aug 21, 2010','Bonus Peaks!','Success!','Set up camp at Dade Lake with Gordon Ye for climbing the NE Ridge of Bear Creek Spire the next day. I had some time left in the day, so I climbed the N Ridge of Rosy Finch Peak, then traversed to Pyramid Peak and descended the W Ridge to the col with the NE Ridge of Bear Creek Spire. A good afternoon out on a lot of cl. 3-4+ knife-edge ridges, though there was a LOT of loose rock too!',NULL),(25,'154383','','/rosy-finch-peak/154383','/rosy-finch-peak/climbers-log/154383/d-110777#110777','Aug 21, 2010','Bonus Peaks!','Success!','Set up camp at Dade Lake with Gordon Ye for climbing the NE Ridge of Bear Creek Spire the next day. I had some time left in the day, so I climbed the N Ridge, then traversed to Pyramid Peak and descended the W Ridge to the col with the NE Ridge of Bear Creek Spire. A good afternoon out on a lot of knife-edge ridges, though there was a LOT of loose rock too!',NULL),(26,'151977','','/tunnabora-peak/151977','/tunnabora-peak/climbers-log/151977/d-110358#110358','Aug 15, 2010','2nd Peak of the Day','Success!','Tagged this on the 2010 Sierra Challenge after doing Morgensen and on my way to Cleaver Pk.',NULL),(27,'197009','','/colosseum-mountain/197009','/colosseum-mountain/climbers-log/197009/d-110352#110352','Aug 14, 2010','Sierra Challenge 2010','Success!','Climbed the N Ridge from Armstrong Canyon before descending the SW slopes to push on to Cedric Wright!',NULL),(28,'154375','','/mount-cedric-wright/154375','/mount-cedric-wright/climbers-log/154375/d-110350#110350','Aug 14, 2010','Nice Peak after Coliseum','Success!','Climbed the cl. 3 NE Ridge from the col on my way over from Colloseum. Descended the E/SE Face on my way to Perkins Pk.',NULL),(29,'151779','','/tenaya-peak/151779','/tenaya-peak/climbers-log/151779/d-109330#109330','Jul 31, 2010','Great Simul-climb','Success!','Led/simul-climbed the NW Buttress with Chris Terry while Dave Millar and Joel  Bernier soloed it beside us. The climbing was easier than expected. Clean, fun rock, easy pro, and easy routefinding. The 5.7 direct finish was also very fun and secure climbing.',NULL),(30,'150222','','/thunderbolt-peak/150222','/thunderbolt-peak/climbers-log/150222/d-106654#106654','Jul 19, 2010','6th time\'s the charm','Success!','#1: October 1, 2005 - via Southwest Chute #1. Fresh snow and high winds made us turn back 200\' below the summit.',NULL),(31,'150406','','/north-palisade/150406','/north-palisade/climbers-log/150406/d-8112#8112','Jun 20, 2010','3 times now?!','Success!','June 20th, 2010 - The last peak of a very long day as Steph and I made a good effort at a Palisade traverse. We descended the E Couloir of the U-Notch in the dark.',NULL),(32,'150505','','/starlight-peak/150505','/starlight-peak/climbers-log/150505/d-106648#106648','Jun 20, 2010','Pink Cowboy Hat','Success!','Steph Abegg and I summited while doing the Palisade Traverse. We brought a pink cowboy hat along as a summit prop!',NULL),(33,'607527','','/little-pfeifferhorn/607527','/little-pfeifferhorn/climbers-log/607527/d-106181#106181','','Tagged','Success!','I had no idea this had a name, but I\'ve gone over it on my way to the Pfeifferhorn.',NULL),(34,'153567','','/reynolds-peak/153567','/reynolds-peak/climbers-log/153567/d-106179#106179','','Bushwack adventure!','Success!','I bushwacked up this in the summer of 2002 from the lake, then back down to the saddle and up another highpoint before I got tired of the brush. I did this with Gary, my first alpine trad partner.',NULL),(35,'467295','','/thayne-peak/467295','/thayne-peak/climbers-log/467295/d-106178#106178','','Thayne Canyon on my way to mt Raymond','Success!','I did this so long ago while on a hike with my dad. 2002? 2000? I really don\'t recall.',NULL),(36,'419369','','/circle-all-peak/419369','/circle-all-peak/climbers-log/419369/d-106177#106177','Jan 29, 2005','Bump on the way to the Knob','Success!','Joe and I tagged this on our way back from climbing Gobblers Knob and Mt Raymond. The summit has nice views of Big Cottonwood Canyon and in the winter you can then shortcut down to the TH.',NULL),(37,'395013','','/patsy-marley/395013','/patsy-marley/climbers-log/395013/d-106173#106173','Jul 21, 2004','Nice views of Wolverine Cirque!','Success!','Did this via:',NULL),(38,'401747','','/preston-peak/401747','/preston-peak/climbers-log/401747/d-106172#106172','Jul 21, 2004','Brighton Ridge Run','Success!','Nice hike, great views, easy routefinding.',NULL),(39,'151177','','/pfeifferhorn/151177','/pfeifferhorn/climbers-log/151177/d-5543#5543','','Picturesque Peak','Success!','May, 2002 - Great day hike on the E Ridge via Red Pine. Hiked from 10 am \'till 3 pm. Celebrated w/ some brewskis with fellow Wasatch Mountain Club hikers. One of my favorite hikes. I\'ve gotta try this peak in the winter. I also have ambitions to do it again as part of the Beatout Ridgerun.',NULL),(40,'150862','','/mount-tamalpais/150862','/mount-tamalpais/climbers-log/150862/d-104241#104241','','Wandering Around','Success!','Hiked this one starting lower down to the West and traversing north of the massif ridge. I have plans to come back and hike this one properly - bike from SF and hike it from the valley. Maybe this summer?',NULL),(41,'150863','','/mount-diablo/150863','/mount-diablo/climbers-log/150863/d-104235#104235','May 30, 2009','Does cycling count?','Success!','I did it RT from Berkeley and made the ride a 100-mile &amp; 10,000 ft gain loop. I think this was a lot harder than hiking up the mountain, and all still under muscle power, so I\'m counting it :-)',NULL),(42,'151534','','/diamond-head-le-ahi-mountain/151534','/diamond-head-le-ahi-mountain/climbers-log/151534/d-104224#104224','','I got the official certificate!','Success!','So I can PROVE that I was there! :-P',NULL),(43,'153125','','/chipman-peak/153125','/chipman-peak/climbers-log/153125/d-100536#100536','Dec 28, 2009','Dry Creek Approach','Success!','Spent two cold nights skinning up Dry Creek with grander plans in the area. In the end I just wandered over and climbed Chipman with Foweezer and Marauders via the saddle/west bowl. Steep snow climb at the top!',NULL),(44,'150514','','/middle-palisade/150514','/middle-palisade/climbers-log/150514/d-96566#96566','Sep 26, 2009','Perfect Day','Success!','Dayhike via the NE Face route with 3 others. We caught alpenglow views from Finger Lake, and we never saw a single cloud the entire day. No one else was on the route, and there was negligible wind on the summit. AND we were back down in time for dinner and beer.',NULL),(45,'151712','','/royce-peak/151712','/royce-peak/climbers-log/151712/d-95671#95671','Sep 12, 2009','Nice Dayhike','Success!','Dayhiked the peak via Merriam Saddle, but bailed on Merriam due to thunderstorms. A chill 12 hrs car-to-car.  Which bump was the summit?',NULL),(46,'153182','','/ptarmigan-point/153182','/ptarmigan-point/climbers-log/153182/d-94844#94844','Aug 28, 2009','Nice Easy Peak','Success!','Hiked from TH to summit via the standard trail over Flat Top\'s summit (1:30 hrs). Couldn\'t tell where Flat Top\'s summit actually was, so I cut off from the trail junction to climb Hallet (2-2:30), and then back across the plateau to climb Ptarmigan Pt via up and down the fun cl. 3 bump on its W slopes (3:00) before descending, with a RT time of 4:20 hrs. Nice trail!',NULL),(47,'151577','','/hallett-peak/151577','/hallett-peak/climbers-log/151577/d-94842#94842','Aug 28, 2009','Nice easy peak','Success!','Hiked from TH to summit via the standard trail over Flat Top\'s summit (1:30 hrs). Couldn\'t tell where Flat Top\'s summit actually was, so I cut off from the trail junction to climb Hallet (2-2:30), and then back across the plateau to climb Ptarmigan Pt (3:00) before descending, with a RT time of 4:20 hrs. Nice trail!',NULL),(48,'152200','','/flattop-mountain/152200','/flattop-mountain/climbers-log/152200/d-94841#94841','Aug 28, 2009','Where is the summit?','Success!','Hiked from TH to summit via the standard trail in 1:30 hrs. Couldn\'t tell where the summit actually was, so I cut off from the trail junction to climb Hallet (2-2:30), and then back across the plateau to climb Ptarmigan Pt (3:00) before descending, with a RT time of 4:20 hrs. Nice trail!',NULL),(49,'150325','','/mount-elbert/150325','/mount-elbert/climbers-log/150325/d-94839#94839','Aug 28, 2009','Getting back in shape','Success!','I hadn\'t exercised at all for the past 3 months and had gained 15 lbs while working in Qatar. This was my first outing since then, and it worked out very nicely with a 2:40 hrs summit time! Nice views from the summit.',NULL),(50,'150452','','/boundary-peak-nevada/150452','/boundary-peak-nevada/climbers-log/150452/d-88768#88768','Jun 5, 2009','Bad Weather 2 Years in a Row','Success!','Climbed the NW Ridge from 7,000 ft in the Chalfant Valley as a start to a traverse of the White Mtns. Horrendous weather and my team mates leaving me solo caused me to rethink plans and bail on the traverse. Snow about this time last year kept me from getting anywhere near Boundary\'s summit, so at least this was an improvement! Maybe next year . . .',NULL),(51,'154164','','/mount-edith/154164','/mount-edith/climbers-log/154164/d-82486#82486','Jul 31, 2008','Scared *&amp;^%less','Success!','Perhaps it was because I was soloing, and out here on my bicycle on a tour from Calgary to Vancouver. Or perhaps it was the loose rock, but this summit made me nervous!',NULL),(52,'154182','','/mount-cory/154182','/mount-cory/climbers-log/154182/d-82484#82484','Jul 31, 2008','Fun Scramble','Success!','This was my first ever Canadian Rockies summit. Fun scramble, and extra memorable linking it up with Mt Edith! I got off the ridge/route near the summit and ended up on some sketchy loose terrain, though, so stick to the ridge!',NULL),(53,'151994','','/mount-fairview/151994','/mount-fairview/climbers-log/151994/d-82477#82477','Aug 3, 2008','Its practically cheating','Success!','How can such an easy climb have such great views? :-D I was almost too lazy to pick my way up here after zoning out, but then I got a spurt of energy and summitted within an hour of leaving Lake Louise.',NULL),(54,'150408','','/mount-temple/150408','/mount-temple/climbers-log/150408/d-82475#82475','Aug 6, 2008','Big Day for the Big Momma','Success!','I doubled back from Yoho National Park on my bike tour to climb this peak. Well worth the return trip and tiring bike approach! Eiffel Peak is also good to tag on in a long day.',NULL),(55,'151866','','/eiffel-peak/151866','/eiffel-peak/climbers-log/151866/d-82473#82473','Aug 6, 2008','Normal Route + Mt Temple','Success!','Tagged Eiffel Peak after Climbing Mt Temple on my bike tour from Calgary to Vancouver.',NULL),(56,'151301','North Route','/mount-nebo/151301','/mount-nebo/climbers-log/151301/d-5542#5542','October, 2002','Route Climbed: North Route Date Climbed: Octo','No','Great hike.  Some of my favorite mountain views are along this route.',NULL),(57,'150199','','/denali/150199','/denali/climbers-log/150199/d-72982#72982','Jun 18, 2008','Buttin\' Out','Success!','Our team originally had its sights set on the West Rib, then the Upper West Rib cutoff, but ultimately we wimped out and climbed the butt. 12 hrs RT from 17k camp. I barely felt the altitude! Great weather. Trip report and photo links coming soon.',NULL),(58,'150701','','/rocky-peak-ridge/150701','/rocky-peak-ridge/climbers-log/150701/d-65498#65498','Sep 2, 2007','Second Adirondack Peak Hiked','Success!','I left my family on the main trail to the summit of Giant and scrambled/jogged over to this summit and back. Round trip was about 40 minutes of huffing and puffing to get out some unspent energy!',NULL),(59,'150557','','/giant-mountain/150557','/giant-mountain/climbers-log/150557/d-65497#65497','Sep 2, 2007','First Hike in the Adirondacks','Success!','The first Adirondack peak that I have climbed, on a Labor Day Weekend visit with the family.  I also jogged over to Rocky Peak Ridge and back without the family to get a good workout before heading down. Nice hike, great weather!',NULL),(60,'150284','','/mount-dana/150284','/mount-dana/climbers-log/150284/d-45518#45518','Oct 22, 2006','from Dana Couloir','Success!','A variety of conditions (from neve to thick brittle ice) made the climb quite interesting and fun. Being sick was not, as I was lethargic the entire day and could barely eat anything!',NULL),(61,'151202','NW Chutes  Descended: NW Ridge of Vagabond Pk','/cloudripper/151202','/cloudripper/climbers-log/151202/d-43598#43598','Sep 9, 2006','NW Chutes  Descended: NW Ridge of Vagabond Pk','Success!','We climbed a chute that put us between Vagabond Pk &amp; Cloudripper. I still climbed Vagabond twice, once when waiting for my friend, and again when we had to surmount it to descend the full NW ridge of Vagabond Pk.  Our chute wasn\'t nearly as bad as it looked - the rock was for the most part stable, so the slog wasn\'t too bad, and the scrambling at the end was fun.',NULL),(62,'153022','NW Chutes on Cloudripper  Descended NW Ridge','/vagabond-peak/153022','/vagabond-peak/climbers-log/153022/d-43597#43597','Sep 9, 2006','NW Chutes on Cloudripper  Descended NW Ridge','Success!','Summited this peak twice - once while waiting for my friend and again when we realized that we would have to surmount the summit in order to descend to the north.',NULL),(63,'151681','','/mount-powell/151681','/mount-powell/climbers-log/151681/d-41962#41962','Aug 6, 2006','Sierra Challenge 2006','Success!','Climbed this peak on the 3rd day of the Sierra Challenge. Ascended via the NE Couloir (fun) and descended the SE Face (sucked) after tagging Pt Wesley. Apparently Bob Burd found a fun class 3 traverse to Mount Powell and I\'m kicking myself for not following him!',NULL),(64,'152754','Zee Tree','/pywiack-dome/152754','/pywiack-dome/climbers-log/152754/d-41951#41951','Jul 23, 2006','Zee Tree','Success!','A fun day on the Dome. Dirk let me lead the first 3 pitches, which were quite thrilling as I am not used to the bolt spacin in Tuolumne Meadows! It started to reain near the end, and Dirk quickly finished the last 2 pitches.  A great climb.',NULL),(65,'150362','','/gannett-peak/150362','/gannett-peak/climbers-log/150362/d-41950#41950','Aug 21, 2006','Nice Dayhike via Titcomb Basin-Gooseneck Pinn','Success!','I had a twisted plan to hike this peak in less than 24 hrs RT from the Pole Creek Trailhead and on August 21st I carried out this plan with my friend Joel Wilson.  We started out extremely sleep deprived, which slowed us down, but we still managed to complete the hike in 23:36! See our trip report for more info and photos.',NULL),(66,'150876','Regular Route','/castle-dome/150876','/castle-dome/climbers-log/150876/d-39560#39560','Feb 11, 2006','Regular Route','Success!','I climbed this peak with Matthew Holliman after bailing on a nearby technical climb. I chose the class 4 friction over the class 3 stairs on the ascent, and I was wishing that I downclimbed it too as the class 3 downclimb had me quite nervous!',NULL),(67,'191302','','/hidden-peak-utah/191302','/hidden-peak-utah/climbers-log/191302/d-39559#39559','','Yet Another Bump on the Hill','Success!','Climbed various times on the Bullion Divide and climbs on the American Fork Twin Peaks.',NULL),(68,'150921','New Rolling Stones, 5.8+ III','/mount-agassiz/150921','/mount-agassiz/climbers-log/150921/d-39558#39558','Jul 14, 2006','New Rolling Stones, 5.8+ III','Success!','Vlad and I had come to the Palisades last weekend to do a traverse from Thunderbolt Peak via the North Couloir to Mt Sill. As we had made our approach to camp the day prior extra fast, we decided to quickly climb Agassiz via the NE Face (II, 5.2).',NULL),(69,'150291','Disappointment Cleaver','/mount-rainier/150291','/mount-rainier/climbers-log/150291/d-36814#36814','May 20, 2006','Disappointment Cleaver','Success!','Weather forced us to bed down at Camp Muir rather than contining on to Igraham Flats Friday night. Snow threatened to shut us down, but by 1am the weather was clear, and we were on the summit by 8am. The sound of a collapsing serac far below was the highlight of the descent.',NULL),(70,'151509','SW Slopes','/junction-peak/151509','/junction-peak/climbers-log/151509/d-27226#27226','Aug 14, 2005','SW Slopes','No','Almost climbed this with the Sierra Challenge crew. I made it as far as the nearly-as-high false summit, 100 ft away.',NULL),(71,'151824','Thor\'s Cellar','/thor-peak/151824','/thor-peak/climbers-log/151824/d-36552#36552','May 6, 2006','Thor\'s Cellar','Success!','Bob Burd, Rick Kent, and I had started out to climb a class \"3\" route on the south face, but when even attempts at Snowshoe aiding on the 5.5 chimney failed, we wandered around and headed up the most interesting looking chute on the SW face of the peak. Our chute consisted of a chockstone and a narrow ice-lined tunnel that required us to climb through one at a time, handing packs off so that we could fit through. It definitely brought back memories of climbing in the Southwest :-)',NULL),(72,'153310','North Couloir','/trojan-peak/153310','/trojan-peak/climbers-log/153310/d-36551#36551','May 6, 2006','North Couloir','Success!','I climbed this nice peak while on a day excursion up George Creek with Bob Burd, Rick Kent, and Michael Graup. I had intended on climbing the NE Couloir and descending the N Couloir, but the sound of snow slides in the NE couloir made me reconsider these plans and hike around to more stable snow.',NULL),(73,'151573','September 25th, 2005','/mount-thompson/151573','/mount-thompson/climbers-log/151573/d-30616#30616','Harrington Couloir','Route Climbed: September 25th, 2005 Date Clim','Success!','fun climb, good friends, and sunny weather. What more could one ask  for?!',NULL),(74,'151224','North Couloir','/mount-gilbert/151224','/mount-gilbert/climbers-log/151224/d-30615#30615','September 24th, 2005','Route Climbed: North Couloir Date Climbed: Se','Success!','Fun climb, although the ice wasn\'t \'in\' yet - just a smattering if ice beneath very cruddy and irregular neve. Harrington Couloir on Mt Thompson was in much better condition.  The climb at the top was fun - the 5.6 variation was fun, although very short.',NULL),(75,'151478','Pioneer Route','/smith-monkey-face/151478','/smith-monkey-face/climbers-log/151478/d-27227#27227','September 3rd, 2005','Route Climbed: Pioneer Route Date Climbed: Se','Success!','Climbed this awesome spire with Dirk on an extended trip to OR to climb the 3 Sisters. I expected that I could just jug up the aid pitch, but instead I had to learn how to aid climb on the spot (and in the dark) to clean the pitch! I never realized how exausting aid climbing was until then :-)\r\rI tried to wimp out at the cave, but Dirk insisted on finishing, and I\'m glad we did! The views were wonderful, and the rappel in the dark was freaky, especially as the wind began spinning me!',NULL),(76,'150844','Contact Crack','/temple-crag/150844','/temple-crag/climbers-log/150844/d-27225#27225','August 11th, 2005','Route Climbed: Contact Crack Date Climbed: Au','Success!','Climbed this as part of the Sierra Challenge. I almost wimped out on the final exposed class 2 traverse to the summit (after free-soloing the 5.2 Contact Crack!), but luckily Matthew was able to lure me over by dangling a runner near me as I scrambled the the rest of the way :-D\r\rIt was a surpise seeing that the summit block could be reached via a class 2 route, as the one mentioned on SP earlier insisted you had to climb the class 4 crack lower down.',NULL),(77,'153021','SE Ridge - descended NW Ridge','/chocolate-peak/153021','/chocolate-peak/climbers-log/153021/d-27224#27224','August 10th, 2005','Route Climbed: SE Ridge - descended NW Ridge ','Success!','Tagged this peak on my way back from an easy day on the Sierra Challenge. The highlight of the peak was the interesting shortcut we took down the NW Ridge onto what I called \"Vanilla Flats\"',NULL),(78,'151840','NE Face, descended S Ridge','/isosceles-peak/151840','/isosceles-peak/climbers-log/151840/d-27223#27223','August 10th, 2005','Route Climbed: NE Face, descended S Ridge Dat','Success!','An anticlimatic summit, but the 4th class headwall climbed to gain the ridge was sure a thrill! A nice easy day on Bob Burd\'s Sierra Challenge, w/ a post-clim B-Day celebration and a pool party.',NULL),(79,'151233','South Ridge','/clyde-spires/151233','/clyde-spires/climbers-log/151233/d-27222#27222','August 9th, 2005','Route Climbed: South Ridge Date Climbed: Augu','Success!','Summitted this peak w/ Bob Burd &amp; Co. on the Sierra Challenge. A fun scramble with some interesting routefinding on the approach. I climbed up and down some interesting 4th class offwidth cracks beside the class 3 variation leading to the summit block from the south.',NULL),(80,'151232','Lamarck Col - S Ridge','/mount-lamarck/151232','/mount-lamarck/climbers-log/151232/d-27221#27221','August 8th, 2005','Route Climbed: Lamarck Col - S Ridge Date Cli','Success!','Fun scramble, with ample low 5th scrambling opportunities - Matt, Jeff, and I had a blast scrambling on the towers and cracks on the peak. Definitely a good consolation prize for wimping out on Mendel.',NULL),(81,'151241','SE Chute - descended West Ridge and South Slopes','/mount-emerson/151241','/mount-emerson/climbers-log/151241/d-27220#27220','August 7th, 2005','Route Climbed: SE Chute - descended West Ridg','Success!','Interesting climb - I wish I could have done the SE Face/Ridge w/ Bob and Glenn, but the water was too much for me. The SE chute was nice at the bottom, filled with a lot of bouldering moves, but the top 2/3 was a slog w/ a lot of branching dead ends.\r\rI discovered the hard way that you can\'t just walk down the SW slopes, even though it looked doable on the topo!',NULL),(82,'151102','NE Face','/merriam-peak/151102','/merriam-peak/climbers-log/151102/d-27219#27219','August 6th, 2005','Route Climbed: NE Face Date Climbed: August 6','Success!','Climbed this with Bob Burds Sierra Challenge posse. A fun scramble on fairly solid rock - definitely much better than the NW Ridge!',NULL),(83,'154274','W slopes - S Ridge - Descended Hour Glass Couloir','/pipsqueak-spire/154274','/pipsqueak-spire/climbers-log/154274/d-27218#27218','August 5th, 2005','Route Climbed: W slopes - S Ridge - Descended','Success!','Climbed both sides of the summit block - what fun it was! Perhaps it is a good warmup for climbing Starlight\'s summit block?',NULL),(84,'150312','Upper Exum','/grand-teton/150312','/grand-teton/climbers-log/150312/d-23630#23630','July 16th, 2005','Route Climbed: Upper Exum Date Climbed: July ','No','Joe Bullough and I made it to the Upper Saddle Rappel via the Upper Exum. High winds and a late time (2pm) forced us to abandon our summit attempt here :_(\r\rWe did this car-to-car, leaving at 1:05 am w/o any sleep from the night prior. The high winds made the descent much more grueling than the climb (TR coming soon), and we didn\'t get back to our car until 10:30 pm. 21:25 hrs on the trail, and I had been awake for 40 hrs!',NULL),(85,'153695','South Ridge, descended East Ridge','/four-gables/153695','/four-gables/climbers-log/153695/d-18852#18852','August 3rd, 2004','Route Climbed: South Ridge, descended East Ri','Success!','An easy stroll from South Basin Mountain.  The East Ridge could be an enjoyable route to climb up with some snow cover.  I still don\'t understand why the official summit with the register is lower than two other nearby points that are higher. Also, from the valley it only looks like one gable - the rest of the ridge just rolls like a wave. Go figure  :-)',NULL),(86,'153374','Traverse from Mt Haeckel, descended Southeast Slope','/mount-wallace/153374','/mount-wallace/climbers-log/153374/d-18847#18847','August 4th, 2004','Route Climbed: Traverse from Mt Haeckel, desc','Success!','The traverse over from Haeckel was fun, but the descent down the Southeast Slope was a nightmare!  I can\'t even imagine how horrible it would be to climb up that slope.\rThe summit block was quite fun to be on, though.',NULL),(87,'151365','Everest Ridge','/mt-timpanogos-ut/151365','/mt-timpanogos-ut/climbers-log/151365/d-18343#18343','January 22, 2005','Route Climbed: Everest Ridge Date Climbed: Ja','No','I made it to the \'step\' and reached the top of the cliffs, but due to lack of a safety line or second ice axe, I decided not to push my luck that day, although now I\'m more determined to go back and finish the route!\r\rDeparture: 2:20am\rReturn: 1:30 pm',NULL),(88,'153420','West Face via Bells Canyon','/north-thunder-mountain/153420','/north-thunder-mountain/climbers-log/153420/d-17653#17653','July 11, 2004','Route Climbed: West Face via Bells Canyon Dat','Success!','Climbed N Thunder Mtn first by cutting over to Thunder Mtn Bowl from the upper reservoir. I then followed the ridgeline (class 3, with some exposure) to S Thunder before descending Bells Canyon. Both summits had very nice registers on top. \rI left the TH at 7:20am and got back at 5:20pm - not too shabby',NULL),(89,'153143','West Ridge via Cardiff Pass','/flagstaff-mountain/153143','/flagstaff-mountain/climbers-log/153143/d-16673#16673','July 16th, 2004','Route Climbed: West Ridge via Cardiff Pass Da','Success!','Fun class 3 scramble, and a very short route - great for an afternoon scramble',NULL),(90,'152831','East Ridge, descended West Ridge','/bighorn-peak-upper-bells-peak/152831','/bighorn-peak-upper-bells-peak/climbers-log/152831/d-16667#16667','October 16th, 2004','Route Climbed: East Ridge, descended West Rid','Success!','Bagged this peak on my way from S Thunder to Lone Pk. I\'d been wanting to do this peak for a while, and the class 3 climbing made my climbing it very worthwhile - the class 3 scrambling has got to be some of the best in the Wasatch!',NULL),(91,'152890','Secret Lake, descended to Sugarloaf/Baldy saddle','/sugarloaf-peak/152890','/sugarloaf-peak/climbers-log/152890/d-16029#16029','July 2004','Route Climbed: Secret Lake, descended to Suga','Success!','Nice steep class 2 hike. I did this peak to start off the Bullion Divide ridge run,  going to White Baldy and down Red Pine, making for a good day of scrambling.',NULL),(92,'152888','Secret Lake, also via Sugarloaf','/mount-baldy-ut/152888','/mount-baldy-ut/climbers-log/152888/d-16028#16028','June 2002, July 2004','Route Climbed: Secret Lake, also via Sugarloa','Success!','Nice easy scramble. Did this peak both times as part of the Bullion Divide ridge run. The second time I did it solo from Sugarloaf to White Baldy and down Red Pine, making for a good day of scrambling.',NULL),(93,'150382','Northwest Ridge','/wilson-peak/150382','/wilson-peak/climbers-log/150382/d-15530#15530','September 5, 2004','Route Climbed: Northwest Ridge Date Climbed: ','No','I attempted this route over Labor Day weekend with Diggler. A big snowstorm passed through the day before and dumped a lot of extremely light snow in the Rockies (a few inches to a few feet deep on top of the rock). This snow made the loose rock on the route very problematic and dangerous. We turned around at the large notch before the ridge\'s intersection with a minor ridge.\rThis place looks awesome with snow cover. When I come back to re-climb the route, I\'ll have to make sure that it is a snow climb!',NULL),(94,'150302','South Ridge via Grouse Gulch','/handies-peak/150302','/handies-peak/climbers-log/150302/d-15529#15529','September 6, 2004','Route Climbed: South Ridge via Grouse Gulch D','Success!','Although the route was easy, the views made the hike very worthwhile - certainly one of my favorite summit views! The 6\"-2\' snow cover from the storm that passed through  on the 4th made it look like the middle of winter!',NULL),(95,'151803','North East Ridge - descended via South Ridge','/mount-watson/151803','/mount-watson/climbers-log/151803/d-15222#15222','August 28th, 2004','Route Climbed: North East Ridge - descended v','Success!','This was the final peak of the day out of a 4 peak grand slam. After doing Bald Mtn, Reids Pk, and Notch Mtn, I continued X-country to the summit of Watson before descending to the Crystal Lake TH. All in all, a great loop to do! Not very hard (3,600\' gain, ca. 12 miles), but the views are wonderful.',NULL),(96,'151806','Notch Lake - descended to The Notch','/notch-mountain/151806','/notch-mountain/climbers-log/151806/d-15221#15221','August 28th, 2004','Route Climbed: Notch Lake - descended to The ','Success!','Fun peak. It has great views of Mt Watson, Reids Pk, and Bald Mountain. Downclimbing the cliffs to the notch offered some fun class 3 chimney downclimbing.',NULL),(97,'151804','Pass Lake - Descended SW face','/reids-peak/151804','/reids-peak/climbers-log/151804/d-15220#15220','August 28, 2004','Route Climbed: Pass Lake - Descended SW face ','Success!','Fun peak for scrambling, and an excellent peak to do after climbing Bald Mountain. I then continued on to Notch Mountain, and Mount Watson via easy cross country and class 2 scrambling.',NULL),(98,'151805','Bald Mountain Trail','/bald-mountain/151805','/bald-mountain/climbers-log/151805/d-15219#15219','August 28th, 2004','Route Climbed: Bald Mountain Trail Date Climb','Success!','Nice easy warm up hike before continuing on to Reids Pk, Notch Mountain, and Mount Watson.',NULL),(99,'150488','North Arete - descended East Couloir','/matterhorn-peak/150488','/matterhorn-peak/climbers-log/150488/d-14562#14562','August 8, 2004','Route Climbed: North Arete - descended East C','Success!','Climbed this route with Dirk (Diggler) and Gordon as a finale to my mountaineering extravaganza in the Sierra. After 7 days on the Sierra Challenge w/ Bob Burd, this was an excellent way to finish up the trip!',NULL),(100,'152909','Schimitar Pass','/mount-jepson/152909','/mount-jepson/climbers-log/152909/d-14561#14561','August  6th, 2004','Route Climbed: Schimitar Pass Date Climbed: A','Success!','I dayhiked this peak as a consolation prize for wussing out on soloing Gandalf Peak on the Palisade Crest for Day #7 of the Sierra Challenge',NULL),(101,'151010','East Arete','/mount-winchell/151010','/mount-winchell/climbers-log/151010/d-14559#14559','August 5, 2004','Route Climbed: East Arete Date Climbed: Augus','Success!','Dayhike day #6 for Sierra Challenge. Round trip hike/scramble 9hrs. Great class 3 scrambling along the entire arete, with greater difficulty and exposure near the top. The views of Agassiz and Thunderbolt were wonderful!',NULL),(102,'152557','East Couloir','/basin-mountain/152557','/basin-mountain/climbers-log/152557/d-14557#14557','August 3rd, 2004','Route Climbed: East Couloir Date Climbed: Aug','Success!','Day 4 of the Sierra Challenge. I took a bad fall in a chimney when a chockstone that I was standing on blew out - gouged my shin pretty bad. Luckily I still had the energy to do the class 4 ridge to South Basin Mountain and traverse to Four Gables!',NULL),(103,'151441','Southeast Ridge','/mount-maclure/151441','/mount-maclure/climbers-log/151441/d-14556#14556','August 1, 2004','Route Climbed: Southeast Ridge Date Climbed: ','Success!','Quite a bear to dayhike in combo with Mt Lyell! Day #2 of the Sierra Challenge. The class 3 scramble along the knife-edge ridgeline was fun, but the talus slog to get to it was a pain - perhaps it would have been better as a spring snowclimb/scramble',NULL),(104,'150494','Lyell Glacier/East Ridge','/mount-lyell/150494','/mount-lyell/climbers-log/150494/d-14555#14555','August 1, 2004','Route Climbed: Lyell Glacier/East Ridge Date ','Success!','Quite a bear to dayhike! Especially with Maclure included. I did this peak as part of the Sierra Challenge, climbing the glacier before angling towards the col to the east, where Joel and I found a nice class 3 ledge system leading to the summit.',NULL),(105,'151839','Ascended from East, descended White Pine','/white-baldy/151839','/white-baldy/climbers-log/151839/d-14171#14171','July 27, 2004','Route Climbed: Ascended from East, descended ','Success!','Did this peak as part of the Bullion Divide Route. I started out at Sugarloaf, then did Mt Baldy, Hidden Pk, all 3 summits of the American Fork Twin Pks, Red Top, Red Baldy, and White Baldy. What a day! I much preferred the east ridge to the NW - it was a bitch coming down!',NULL),(106,'152858','Catherine Pass, descended via Mt Millicent','/mount-wolverine-mount-tuscarora/152858','/mount-wolverine-mount-tuscarora/climbers-log/152858/d-14003#14003','July 21st, 2004','Route Climbed: Catherine Pass, descended via ','Success!','Fun climb, nice views. I was very suprised as to how much it and Tuscarora changed appearances from different views. I was also awestruck by the cirque. Although small, it is rugged and is certainly the most accessible cirque in the Wasatch!',NULL),(107,'152857','Mt Wolverine, descended to Twin Lakes Reservoir','/mount-millicent/152857','/mount-millicent/climbers-log/152857/d-14002#14002','July 21st, 2004','Route Climbed: Mt Wolverine, descended to Twi','Success!','I\'d been wanting to do this peak for a while. Fun little peak with nice views. It was easier to climb and descend than I had expected. I\'ll definitely have to come back here in the winter!',NULL),(108,'152856','Twin Lakes Pass','/honeycomb-cliffs/152856','/honeycomb-cliffs/climbers-log/152856/d-14001#14001','July 21st, 2004','Route Climbed: Twin Lakes Pass Date Climbed: ','Success!','This final leg of my extended version of the Brighton Ridge Run was pretty tiring, but the views were well worth it. Overall a very interesting route with some fun mining and geological points of interest along the way.',NULL),(109,'152855','Brighton Ridge Run','/sunset-peak/152855','/sunset-peak/climbers-log/152855/d-13999#13999','July 21st, 2004','Route Climbed: Brighton Ridge Run Date Climbe','Success!','Awesome views of Little Cottonwood Canyon and the Cottonwood Ridge!',NULL),(110,'152854','Snake Creek Pass trails','/mount-majestic-clayton-peak/152854','/mount-majestic-clayton-peak/climbers-log/152854/d-13992#13992','July 21, 2004','Route Climbed: Snake Creek Pass trails Date C','Success!','Nice hike. Beautiful wildflowers. I went on to hike Pioneer Peak, Sunset Peak, Mt Tuscarora, Mt Wolverine, Mt Millicent, and the Honeycomb Cliffs in a nice ridgerun gaining over 6,000 ft',NULL),(111,'152853','Brighton Ridge Run','/pioneer-peak/152853','/pioneer-peak/climbers-log/152853/d-13991#13991','July 21, 2004','Route Climbed: Brighton Ridge Run Date Climbe','Success!','Nice hike, great views, easy routefinding.',NULL),(112,'151272','South Ridge','/sundial-peak/151272','/sundial-peak/climbers-log/151272/d-13742#13742','July 13, 2004','Route Climbed: South Ridge Date Climbed: July','Success!','Nice fun hike. The scrambling was interesting, but it was much better along the Cottonwood Ridge. I\'ll have to do this peak under snow conditions!',NULL),(113,'151964','Bells Canyon-Traverse from N Thunder','/south-thunder-mountain/151964','/south-thunder-mountain/climbers-log/151964/d-13653#13653','July 11, 2004','Route Climbed: Bells Canyon-Traverse from N T','Success!','Climbed N Thunder Mtn first by cutting over to Thunder Mtn Bowl from the upper reservoir. I then followed the ridgeline (class 3, with some exposure) to S Thunder before descending Bells Canyon.  Both summits had very nice registers on top. \rI left the TH at 7:20am and got back at 5:20pm - not too shabby',NULL),(114,'152752','Ferguson Canyon - West Ridge','/storm-mountain/152752','/storm-mountain/climbers-log/152752/d-13203#13203','June 6th, 2004','Route Climbed: Ferguson Canyon - West Ridge D','Success!','Nice fun hike. The trail was a little rough, but the views were great. It was a nice suprise to find a summit register on top inside a Geocache',NULL),(115,'151902','Deer Creek ascent, SE slope and Dry Creek Descent','/box-elder-peak/151902','/box-elder-peak/climbers-log/151902/d-12706#12706','June 3rd, 2004','Route Climbed: Deer Creek ascent, SE slope an','Success!','Nice scenic hike. It didn\'t seem too steep, but the snow sliver on the ridgeline allowed for some steep step kicking. On top there were thousands of lady bugs, which my friend Alan and I had originally mistaken for algea on the rocks! \rAfter securing a shuttle ride from his girlfriend, Alan and I dropped down the southeast side, doing a nice standing glissade down a few hundred feet of a snow sliver berfore traversing on a pack trail north to the Dry Creek Trail.\r\rThis peak was very scenic and I hope to return for some skiing or an earlier spring snow climb!',NULL),(116,'150499','North Face (Classic Route)','/mount-ritter/150499','/mount-ritter/climbers-log/150499/d-12535#12535','May 25th, 2004','Route Climbed: North Face (Classic Route) Dat','Success!','Climbed Ritter right after doing Banner Pk. I ascended the N face via the Classic variation, but ducked into the 2nd class chute on the west rather than taking the ledges, since the traverse looked shaky and I was racing against some incoming storm clouds.\r\rWith snow, the entire route was very steep, with some fun intermixed class 3. The snow was shallow (perhaps 1/2 inch) before hardening to an ice-like consistency, which made for good cramponing.\r\rI descended by glissading down the Clyde variation to my camp above Lake Ediza.',NULL),(117,'150963','West slope from R/B Saddle','/banner-peak/150963','/banner-peak/climbers-log/150963/d-12534#12534','May 25th, 2004','Route Climbed: West slope from R/B Saddle Dat','Success!','Hiked in and camped above Lake Ediza the day before. I left camp at 4:10, took an easy pace and reached the saddle by 6am, and the summit shortly after 6:40. I couldn\'t find the summit register, nor could I easily tell what lump of rocks was the high point, so I traversed the summit ridge before descending to the saddle to continue on to Mt Ritter.',NULL),(118,'150438','West Face','/mount-williamson/150438','/mount-williamson/climbers-log/150438/d-12533#12533','May 22nd, 2004','Route Climbed: West Face Date Climbed: May 22','Success!','The snow was pretty scarce, but it did cover the important areas such as most of Williamson Bowl and most of the crappy scree in the West Face Chute. The 3rd class at the top was straightforward and free of snow, although there was a lot of ice in the bottom chimney that allowed some fun crampon front-pointing while I used my hands to steady myself.\r\rSadly I couldn\'t find the summit register!  :-(\r\rOnly 3 more CA 14ers to go!',NULL),(119,'151452','Northwest Chute','/mount-leconte/151452','/mount-leconte/climbers-log/151452/d-12320#12320','May 15th, 2004','Route Climbed: Northwest Chute Date Climbed: ','Success!','Nice climb. I bagged this one on my way back from Corcoran.  The route was rather anticlimatic, though, since the waterfall pitch wasn\'t as formidable as I had expected!  Apart from cold hands resulting from handjamming in ice-filled cracks, and some akward chimney work, the 15ft scramble wasn\'t too precarious - I think there were more dangerous scrambling portions later on along the traverse to Corcoran!\rI had meant to continue on to do Mallory and Irvine, but sadly I was too slow after having lugged a rope and pro all the way up.  Perhaps another day!',NULL),(120,'151820','Traverse from LeConte','/mount-corcoran/151820','/mount-corcoran/climbers-log/151820/d-12319#12319','May 15th, 2004','Route Climbed: Traverse from LeConte Date Cli','Success!','Fun snow/ice/rock scramble! Although the rock and soil in the chutes was very slippery, there was enough snow cover to avoid most of it.  The highlight of the route was the steep snow sliver that Joel and I climbed to get underneath the chockstone!',NULL),(121,'150221','West Ridge','/white-mountain-peak/150221','/white-mountain-peak/climbers-log/150221/d-11243#11243','March 22, 2004','Route Climbed: West Ridge Date Climbed: March','Success!','Am I the first one to climb this route on summitpost?\rGorgeous route, LOTS of elevation gain.  There was only about 10% snow cover beginning at 12,000 ft.  It should be a fun route to do with more snow cover!\r\rP.S.  I disagree with Stephen Porcella\'s class 2 rating in his \"Climbing California\'s Fourteeners\" book.  The ridgeline along the +13,000 ft peak before reaching the final slope is definitely class 3 (see my photos) unless one drops below it about one thousand feet and does a traverse on steep slopes!!',NULL),(122,'150246','Cottonwood Lakes','/mount-langley/150246','/mount-langley/climbers-log/150246/d-11242#11242','March 25th, 2004','Route Climbed: Cottonwood Lakes Date Climbed:','Success!','Climbed Mt Langley via the pass north of Old Army pass.  Road was closed from 8,200 ft, so it was a long approach! 100% snow cover began at 9,200ft.  26 miles round trip with a total of 7,400 ft of elevation gain! Did it 1/2 day in, full day to summit, 1/2 day out.  Quite tiring since I did the West Ridge of White Mountain the day before, and Roundtop 2 days before that!',NULL),(123,'150503','Crescent Moon Couloir','/round-top/150503','/round-top/climbers-log/150503/d-11080#11080','March 20, 2004','Route Climbed: Crescent Moon Couloir Date Cli','Success!','Great climb!  Good weather, decent snow, sweet views.  The steepness of the upper part of the couloir was really exciting!',NULL),(124,'150414','North Ridge (our own variation)','/lassen-peak/150414','/lassen-peak/climbers-log/150414/d-10965#10965','March 13th, 2004','Route Climbed: North Ridge (our own variation','Success!','Great climb!  Hiked up to the end of the Chaos Crags the first night.  Climbed the peak saturday via a slighlty different route than the planned north ridge.  Steep snow, wild terrain!  The summit bowl was great too, although I could have done without the giant metal dildo on the higher south summit.',NULL),(125,'150430','North East Ridge','/mount-tallac/150430','/mount-tallac/climbers-log/150430/d-10779#10779','2/29/04','Route Climbed: North East Ridge Date Climbed:','Success!','Great snowshoe hike!  I really wish that I had brought my skis!',NULL),(126,'152297','The gulley from Henry Fork','/gunsight-peak/152297','/gunsight-peak/climbers-log/152297/d-10308#10308','September 1999','Route Climbed: The gulley from Henry Fork Dat','Success!','Nice hike, although I did have to sit out a hailstorm out in the open up there, and the lightning got frighteningly close.  There\'s no where to hide in the bleak flat tundra plain near the summit!',NULL),(127,'152296','Elbow Fork, Ridgeline','/mount-aire/152296','/mount-aire/climbers-log/152296/d-10307#10307','Many times, all seasons','Route Climbed: Elbow Fork, Ridgeline Date Cli','Success!','Every time I head up this peak I have an excellent time.',NULL),(128,'152266','Porter Fork - Descended via Thayne Canyon','/gobblers-knob/152266','/gobblers-knob/climbers-log/152266/d-10243#10243','August 2001','Route Climbed: Porter Fork - Descended via Th','Success!','Nice hike with a sustained steep trail. Not technical in the least bit, but good for exercise and getting outside. \rI went on to climb Mt Raymond via the North East Ridge.',NULL),(129,'151268','Triple Traverse','/sunrise-peak/151268','/sunrise-peak/climbers-log/151268/d-8636#8636','October 18th, 2003','Route Climbed: Triple Traverse Date Climbed: ','Success!','Nice peak, beautiful scramble :) Nice stop along my variation of the Triple Traverse - came up Broad Fork Twin Peaks from Lisa Falls in Little Cottonwood Canyon (class 4-5?), did the traverse, and descended down Broad Fork.  \rI have to try this peak in the winter  : )\r\rIs it just me, or are most of the Utah peak summit logs signed by the same 5 or 6 people?',NULL),(130,'150269','Tiple Traverse','/mt-dromedary/150269','/mt-dromedary/climbers-log/150269/d-8635#8635','October 18th, 2003','Route Climbed: Tiple Traverse Date Climbed: O','Success!','Nice peak, beautiful scramble  :)  Great way to end my variation of the Triple Traverse - came up Broad Fork Twin Peaks from Lisa Falls in Little Cottonwood Canyom (class4-5?), did the traverse, and descended down Broad Fork',NULL),(131,'151269','Cecret Lake/Traverse','/devil-s-castle/151269','/devil-s-castle/climbers-log/151269/d-8634#8634','October 19th, 2003','Route Climbed: Cecret Lake/Traverse Date Clim','Success!','Nice fun scramble. My friend Peter and I were looking for something short yet fun to do, and this scramble was perfect. Good opportunities along the way to try various routes and make the route harder  :)   \rI didn\'t like the loose rock much, though',NULL),(132,'151974','North East Ridge and South West Ridge','/mount-raymond/151974','/mount-raymond/climbers-log/151974/d-8609#8609','May, 2002 and September 2002','Route Climbed: North East Ridge and South Wes','Success!','Great climb any time of year. Did this peak in May with the Wasatch Mountain Club - it was a nice snow hike with a lot of glissading on the descent coming from Mill B.\rCame back in the fall to bag Raymond and Gobblers Knob, ascending Bowmans Fork and descending Thayne Canyon',NULL),(133,'151973','East Ridge via Bullion Divide','/red-baldy/151973','/red-baldy/climbers-log/151973/d-8608#8608','June 2002','Route Climbed: East Ridge via Bullion Divide ','Success!','Nice scramble, although I do wish that I had a helmet on the climb! Descended via White Pine Fork - a very long boulder-hopping extravaganza down to the trail and then a nice 3mph stroll back to the car. \rGot back to SLC and had a celebratory late lunch with my Wasatch Mountain Club comrads at the mouth of Big Cottonwood Canyon and showered.  I love how the Wasatch Mountains give you teh opportunity to do those things on the same day as the climb!',NULL),(134,'151755','Bullion Divide','/american-fork-twin-peaks/151755','/american-fork-twin-peaks/climbers-log/151755/d-8605#8605','June, 2002','Route Climbed: Bullion Divide Date Climbed: J','Success!','Nice scramble. I\'d been wanting to do this peak for a while. \rAn interesting note - along the lower part of the ridgeline between the tram and American Fork Twin Peaks, on the rocks, there were bolts. I wonder what they\'er used for, since exposure certainly didn\'t require placing protection.  Maybe something to do with avalanche control?',NULL),(135,'151751','many routes','/grandeur-peak/151751','/grandeur-peak/climbers-log/151751/d-8587#8587','Many times, all seasons','Route Climbed: many routes Date Climbed: Many','Success!','This is a nice peak to climb, although for some reason flies love to hang around the summit in the summer.  I\'d say my two favorite ascents were from the northwest ridge and snowshoeing up Church Fork in the winter.\rI\'m kicking myself yet again since this is another peak that I\'d been thinking of doing a page  on for a while.',NULL),(136,'151952','Three Amigos Loop','/mount-mellenthin/151952','/mount-mellenthin/climbers-log/151952/d-8585#8585','June, 2003','Route Climbed: Three Amigos Loop Date Climbed','Success!','Nice end to a nice round trip peakbagging extravaganza in the La Sals.  I\'d been meaning to make a page for the peak since June, but I dragged my heels about getting it done. Now I\'m banging my head from the missed opportunity! and by 2 days!  AAARRGG!!!!',NULL),(137,'150495','Whitney Trail (aka. Switchback hell)','/mount-muir/150495','/mount-muir/climbers-log/150495/d-8534#8534','October 11, 2003','Route Climbed: Whitney Trail (aka. Switchback','Success!','Took a little detour on my descent from climbing Mt Whitney\'s mountaineers route. It certainly had the same feel as the East Ridge of Mt Russell!\rThe route descriptions for the type of scrambling to expect were accurate. I was suprised at how short the scramble was from the trail. Also, finding where to go up was a little challenging, but by comparing landmarks and phtos courtesy of summitpost we were able to find the route.',NULL),(138,'150227','Mountaineers Route','/mount-whitney/150227','/mount-whitney/climbers-log/150227/d-8533#8533','October 11, 2003','Route Climbed: Mountaineers Route Date Climbe','Success!','Dayhiked mountaineers route and bagged Muir on the way down the main trail. Definitely one of the more scenic climbs that I\'ve done!',NULL),(139,'150513','From the U-Notch','/polemonium-peak/150513','/polemonium-peak/climbers-log/150513/d-8111#8111','September 20th, 2003','Route Climbed: From the U-Notch Date Climbed:','Success!','Nice summit. I had an excellent view of the class 4 descent on Sill that Dirk and I had downclimbed in the dark earlier in the month.  The climb from the U-notch was shorter than the Chimney variation to North Palisade, but it was definitely more difficult!\r   While descending the west side of the U-notch in the dark wasn\'t too fun, it was definitely better than returning at another date to climb Polemonium.  Thanks for talking me into sneaking one more summit in that day, Dirk.  : -)',NULL),(140,'150410','Swiss Arete','/mount-sill/150410','/mount-sill/climbers-log/150410/d-7507#7507','August 23rd','Route Climbed: Swiss Arete Date Climbed: Augu','Success!','Great climb. Took longer than expected, though, so we had to find our way down in the dark and ended up sleeping at the Glacier Notch until dawn.\rWe never encountered what seemed to be the \'reach around\' move, but we did encouter a 5.8 (maybe 5.9?) crack on the left side of the ridge which was the crux of the climb for us.',NULL),(141,'150473','West Ridge','/mount-conness/150473','/mount-conness/climbers-log/150473/d-7274#7274','August 17, 2003','Route Climbed: West Ridge Date Climbed: Augus','Success!','REALLY long \'day\' for a climb.  After leaving a little late and getting a slow start on the ridge, we got caught in the dark after the first 3 or 4 pitches and had to climb the rest of the ridge in the dark.  As a result, we belayed all of the pitches until the final 300 feet of 3rd class scrambling, with us summitting at 5am the following day.  By the time we got back to the car, we\'d been on the move for 24 hours.',NULL),(142,'150441','North RIb','/mount-tyndall/150441','/mount-tyndall/climbers-log/150441/d-6832#6832','July 26th, 2003','Route Climbed: North RIb Date Climbed: July 2','Success!','It was a nice day-hike to the summit.  I left the trailhead at 2:40 am, summitted at about 11:30 am, and got back to my car by 8 PM.  I tried to descend via the Northwest Ridge, but got into terrain that was much more difficult than class 2 when bypassing the minaret, so I traversed across the north slabs to go back down the North Rib.',NULL),(143,'150515','East Ridge','/mount-russell/150515','/mount-russell/climbers-log/150515/d-6424#6424','7/5/03','Route Climbed: East Ridge Date Climbed: 7/5/0','Success!','Great climb!  It definitely has been the most exposed route that I\'ve done to date.  I climbed this peak with Suet Fei Li and Joel Wilson as part of a trip with CHAOS.  \rI\'ve gotta come back to try the Russell-Whitney Traverse that Bob Burd did in the \'02 Sierra Challenge.',NULL),(144,'151290','Cardiff Pass ; Cardiff Pass','/mount-superior-monte-cristo/151290','/mount-superior-monte-cristo/climbers-log/151290/d-6168#6168','June 19th, 2003;  January 2004','Route Climbed: Cardiff Pass ; Cardiff Pass Da','Success!','Nice easy hike and scramble. Some exposure, but nothing too bad.  It was much nicer than when I tried it 3 weeks ago. Although the peak was still covered in snow, I kept sinking in to my knee caps and would get stuck and tripped on the hidden logs and scree!  I\'ll have to try it with snow again sometime; maybe earlier in the spring.\r\rGreat winter dayclimb!',NULL),(145,'150188','Green Butte Route','/mount-shasta/150188','/mount-shasta/climbers-log/150188/d-6139#6139','January, 2003','Route Climbed: Green Butte Route Date Climbed','No','We turned around at 11,000 feet after 14 climbers coming down the ridge said that the snow in the mixed climbing was too hard to penetrate easily with an ice axe and a rope was needed, which we lacked.  My group then traversed into Avalanche Gulch at the highest flat point in hopes of camping there and summiting via that route to avoid the mixed climbing.  Since we were pelted by chunks of rock and ice, and the snow was windswept to bullet proof ice, we decided to descend and try another day.  I might have that day on June 29th as I try to climb the peak via the Cleer Creek route with some members of CHAOS (Cal Hiking and Outdoor Society)',NULL),(146,'151580','South Willow','/deseret-peak/151580','/deseret-peak/climbers-log/151580/d-6136#6136','July, 2002','Route Climbed: South Willow Date Climbed: Jul','Success!','Nice steep hike to the top. Great views!',NULL),(147,'151267','Big Willow','/lone-peak/151267','/lone-peak/climbers-log/151267/d-6133#6133','May 31, 2003','Route Climbed: Big Willow  Date Climbed: May ','Success!','Great 6 hour climb to the top. 100% snow cover began suddenly at 8,800 feet.  The climb up the 800ft high cirque was impressive.  The slope got up to 45-50 degrees, with solid scrambling on granite averaging an even steeper slope higher up before the final mixed climbing along the ridgeline.',NULL),(148,'150376','Standard (via Gunsight pass)','/kings-peak/150376','/kings-peak/climbers-log/150376/d-5541#5541','September, 2000','Route Climbed: Standard (via Gunsight pass) D','Success!','Long hike!  The views and solitude were certainly worth it!  I only saw 1 group of people on the whole hike.',NULL),(149,'150522','Deaf Smith Canyon','/broads-fork-twin-peaks/150522','/broads-fork-twin-peaks/climbers-log/150522/d-5540#5540','June, 2002','Route Climbed: Deaf Smith Canyon Date Climbed','Success!','Great hike!  It was a record elevation gain on a trail for me.  The routefinding was a little tricky, but the views made it well worth it!  Definitely one of my favorite peaks in the Wasatch',NULL),(150,'150493','North Slope','/split-mountain/150493','/split-mountain/climbers-log/150493/d-5533#5533','October 2002','Route Climbed: North Slope Date Climbed: Octo','Success!','What a day hike!  We got lost in the thick brush on the hike down in the dark, though.  Only took us 1 hour to find the trail again.',NULL),(151,'151567','Sawtooth Canyon','/notch-peak/151567','/notch-peak/climbers-log/151567/d-5516#5516','October 2001','Route Climbed: Sawtooth Canyon Date Climbed: ','Success!','Great hike!  Excellent trail for the hiker who wants solitude and breathtaking views.',NULL),(152,'151263','North Face Route','/mount-olympus/151263','/mount-olympus/climbers-log/151263/d-5344#5344','August, 2000','Route Climbed: North Face Route Date Climbed:','Success!','Very long and steep scramble. Makes the trail look like a piece of cake. Brought way too little water though. I\'ve never gotten so dehydrated before or since.',NULL),(153,'158138','','/the-south-face/158138','/the-south-face/climbers-log/158138/d-137612#137612','May 8, 2012','Nice First Wall','Success!','Topped out at midnight. Fortunately the rappels all went smoothly in the dark! It was very windy climbing during the day, but the wind had stopped by nightfall. We had a great full moon for the bivy at Dinner Ledge and the nighttime climbing! We also climbed &amp; hauled P1 the night of the approach on account of the full moon and nice ledge up there. Ants left us alone.',NULL),(154,'157738','','/east-arete/157738','/east-arete/climbers-log/157738/d-119809#119809','Feb 13, 2011','Full East Arete in Winter','Success!','Vitaliy and I started at the saddle between Magic McGee &amp; the 13,000 ft subpeak and climbed the entire ridge. Boots &amp; packs made it more fun. So did the snow cave bivy from 100\' below the summit plateau.',NULL),(155,'157862','','/west-slabs-route/157862','/west-slabs-route/climbers-log/157862/d-117107#117107','Jun 4, 2005','Cell Phone On Route','Success!','I climbed this with Brenton Peterson. I remember on one pitch he got a cell call and stopped to answer his phone and talk on it :-) Also did a little bit of simul-climbing to reach nicer belay ledges a few times.',NULL),(156,'248606','','/the-great-white-icicle/248606','/the-great-white-icicle/climbers-log/248606/d-47956#47956','Dec 30, 2006','Finally','Success!','After being rebuffed by winter thaws over my previous winter breaks, I finally got to climb this thing. A great climb, and every pitch was quite unique.',NULL),(157,'640956','','/west-ridge/640956','/west-ridge/climbers-log/640956/d-108521#108521','Jul 17, 2010','Fun exploration','Success!','Climbed the peak via the West Ridge with Vitaliy. Careful routfinding kept the route at cl. 3 to cl.4-? Incredible exposure, and great scrambling! I couldn\'t tell which summit was the highest and couldn\'t locate the register, so I climbed the three obviously highest summits.',NULL),(158,'155838','','/north-couloir/155838','/north-couloir/climbers-log/155838/d-113073#113073','Sep 25, 2010','Fun ice lead','Success!','Great ice climb! The ice was more brittle along the moat than it was out on the face. Started the first belay in a moat to the side of the couloir &amp; led 3 pitches to the top.',NULL),(159,'155740','','/northwest-arete/155740','/northwest-arete/climbers-log/155740/d-112692#112692','Sep 18, 2010','Loooong Dayhike','Success!','Dayhiked via NW Arete from Happy Isles TH with Joel Wilson and Heyning Cheng. I carried a rope and rack to lead the exposed sections for the others, and it came in handy! I started on the 4th class crack, but found two sections that I\'d say were 5.4-5.5 (so \'classic\' Sierra cl. 4?). We avoided the bushwack hell on the way up but couldn\'t avoid it on the way down.',NULL),(160,'163704','','/men-at-work/163704','/men-at-work/climbers-log/163704/d-112386#112386','Sep 6, 2010','Workin\' hard for the money! So hard for the m','Success!','September 6, 2010 - TRed the right N Side, descended Men at Work after cleaning the top-ropes.',NULL),(161,'162276','','/right-side-topropes/162276','/right-side-topropes/climbers-log/162276/d-112385#112385','Sep 6, 2010','Great Potential for FHFAs!','Success!','I downclimbed every line off the 3 bolts on the right cluster of climbs. The ratings are a joke - maybe the left 5.6 is correct, but everything else seemed easier. My friend Daniel climbed the right 5.10a route without using hands on the rock (First Hands Free Ascent?).',NULL),(162,'156712','','/south-ridge/156712','/south-ridge/climbers-log/156712/d-112384#112384','Sep 11, 2010','down, up, and down again!','Success!','Led the first and third pitch of the N Arete &amp; simul-climbed to the summit. Descended the S Ridge, taking a difficult line staying on the crest the entire way (cl. 4-5). Then I realized I left my sneakers on the summit, so I climbed up and down an easier line utilizing the ledge system to the east cl. 3).',NULL),(163,'161702','','/north-ar-te/161702','/north-ar-te/climbers-log/161702/d-112383#112383','Sep 11, 2010','In the Area, and 5.7? Really?','Success!','so I couldn\'t pass off ticking off one of the routes listed in Croft\'s guidebook :-). Led the first and third pitch of the N Arete &amp; simul-climbed to the summit. The first pitch really felt like 5.5 to me, and I almost climbed through the crux before placing my first piece of pro.',NULL),(164,'158258','','/south-slope/158258','/south-slope/climbers-log/158258/d-112378#112378','Sep 12, 2010','2X','Success!','September 12th, 2010 - Climbed NW Books - Descended S Slopes - A nice easy trad lead, and it was nice to see that I remembered where this descend route went!',NULL),(165,'158908','','/northwest-books/158908','/northwest-books/climbers-log/158908/d-112379#112379','Sep 12, 2010','Nice 5.6','Success!','Led P1 &amp; the topout walkoff. Fun, easy climb! Next time I\'ll have to do the 5.9 variation. It looked like fun, and not too long, especially with the fixed piece.',NULL),(166,'155724','','/south-to-north-traverse/155724','/south-to-north-traverse/climbers-log/155724/d-111929#111929','Sep 4, 2010','Wonderful Climb!','Success!','Led two pitches to the crest, and simul-climbed to the North Summit at about the same speed as some of the other soloists. The 5.7 knob/crack pitch was a bit much with a heavy pack on so I had to ditch it at the notch to finish the pitch - stout!',NULL),(167,'155734','','/se-buttress/155734','/se-buttress/climbers-log/155734/d-111279#111279','Aug 28, 2010','Cold and Windy','Success!','Despite the winds and occasional snow/hail flurries, the weather stayed just good enough for us to finish the climb. Fun route! The chimney was quite the pain in the butt with a pack on, though, but good practice leading offwidth as well!',NULL),(168,'157054','','/northeast-ridge/157054','/northeast-ridge/climbers-log/157054/d-110782#110782','Aug 22, 2010','Nice Simul-Climb','Success!','High winds left me and Gordon Ye uncertain about climbing the route, but luckily the winds had eased off by the time we started the route. A great climb, and next time I\'ll be back for the North Ridge.',NULL),(169,'165948','','/north-ridge/165948','/north-ridge/climbers-log/165948/d-110778#110778','Aug 21, 2010','Bonus Peaks!','Success!','Set up camp at Dade Lake with Gordon Ye for climbing the NE Ridge of Bear Creek Spire the next day. I had some time left in the day, so I climbed the N Ridge, then traversed to Pyramid Peak and descended the W Ridge to the col with the NE Ridge of Bear Creek Spire. A good afternoon out on a lot of knife-edge ridges, though there was a LOT of loose rock too!',NULL),(170,'205503','','/sw-slopes/205503','/sw-slopes/climbers-log/205503/d-110355#110355','Aug 14, 2010','Easy and Fast Descent to Linkup Cedric Wright','Success!','Climbed the N Ridge from Armstrong Canyon before descending the SW slopes to push on to Cedric Wright. The sandy slopes were a nice break from all of the talus.',NULL),(171,'165922','','/south-east-slope/165922','/south-east-slope/climbers-log/165922/d-110354#110354','Aug 14, 2010','Sierra Challenge 2010 Descent Route','Success!','Climbed the cl. 3 NE Ridge from the col on my way over from Colloseum. Descended the E/SE Face on my way to Perkins Pk.',NULL),(172,'165924','','/ne-ridge-from-cedric-colosseum-saddle/165924','/ne-ridge-from-cedric-colosseum-saddle/climbers-log/165924/d-110353#110353','Aug 14, 2010','Sierra Challenge 2010','Success!','Climbed the cl. 3 NE Ridge from the col on my way over from Colloseum. Descended the E/SE Face on my way to Perkins Pk.',NULL),(173,'165606','','/se-slopes/165606','/se-slopes/climbers-log/165606/d-82478#82478','Aug 3, 2008','It\'s practically cheating','Success!','How can such an easy climb have such great views? :-D I was almost too lazy to pick my way up here after zoning out, but then I got a spurt of energy and summitted within an hour of leaving Lake Louise.',NULL),(174,'234383','','/aquaknobby/234383','/aquaknobby/climbers-log/234383/d-109333#109333','Aug 1, 2010','Thrilling Climb','Success!','Led the 5.6R first pitch (slicker than expected!) and the 5.8 3rd pitch, which was really fun and solid.',NULL),(175,'158576','','/sw-ridge/158576','/sw-ridge/climbers-log/158576/d-109332#109332','Jul 31, 2010','Nice easy descent','Success!','Led/simul-climbed the NW Buttress with Chris Terry while Dave Millar and Joel  Bernier soloed it beside us. The climbing was easier than expected. Clean, fun rock, easy pro, and easy routefinding. The 5.7 direct finish was also very fun and secure climbing.',NULL),(176,'158564','','/nw-buttress/158564','/nw-buttress/climbers-log/158564/d-109331#109331','Jul 31, 2010','Great Simul-climb','Success!','Led/simul-climbed the NW Buttress with Chris Terry while Dave Millar and Joel  Bernier soloed it beside us. The climbing was easier than expected. Clean, fun rock, easy pro, and easy routefinding. The 5.7 direct finish was also very fun and secure climbing.',NULL),(177,'167136','','/north-couloir/167136','/north-couloir/climbers-log/167136/d-106687#106687','Jun 20, 2010','Two very different routes','No','#4: September 5-7, 2009 - via N Couloir with Jonathan Bye and Henry Steinberg. Bergschrund was a challenging brittle water ice on alpine ice climb, but a memorable lead. We then took the \'NW Buttress\' to the top. Took longer than expected due to the ice and my friends decided they didn\'t like the idea of sleeping on the ridge, so we bailed down the SW Chute #1 after finishing the route. Doh!',NULL),(178,'161858','','/northwest-ridge/161858','/northwest-ridge/climbers-log/161858/d-108256#108256','Jul 19, 2010','Tricky Route Finding!','Success!','Climbed the ridge with Vitaliy from our camp on the Palisade Glacier. All was going well until we reached the notch. From there we spent the rest of the day having routefinding issues, especially near the very end!',NULL),(179,'156888','','/the-summit-block/156888','/the-summit-block/climbers-log/156888/d-108257#108257','Jul 19, 2010','via NW Ridge','Success!','Climbed the ridge with Vitaliy from our camp on the Palisade Glacier. All was going well until we reached the notch. From there we spent the rest of the day having routefinding issues, especially near the very end!',NULL),(180,'157840','','/north-face-trail/157840','/north-face-trail/climbers-log/157840/d-107800#107800','','Several Times','Success!','One of my favorite hikes in the Wasatch! Stupid private development . . .',NULL),(181,'634376','','/east-arete/634376','/east-arete/climbers-log/634376/d-107700#107700','Aug 5, 2004','Fun scramble!','Success!','Dayhike day #6 for Sierra Challenge. Round trip hike/scramble 9hrs. Great class 3 scrambling along the entire arete, with greater difficulty and exposure near the top. The views of Agassiz and Thunderbolt were wonderful!',NULL),(182,'159004','','/southeast-side-via-agassiz-col/159004','/southeast-side-via-agassiz-col/climbers-log/159004/d-107099#107099','Jul 15, 2006','Epic Late Night Descent','Success!','We descended this route after accidentally climbing a new route on the N Face of Agassiz. Soft snow earlier in the day suckered us into leaving our crampons at camp, so when we descended at night, the snow on the descent was too hard and icy to walk on! By avoiding the snow patches and climbing closer to the ridgeline, the route is broken low-5th class.',NULL),(183,'155568','','/southwest-chute-number-1/155568','/southwest-chute-number-1/climbers-log/155568/d-106686#106686','Sep 6, 2009','Twice and I still don\'t like this route','No','#1: October 1, 2005 - via Southwest Chute #1. Fresh snow and high winds made us turn back 200\' below the summit. I really didn\'t like the loose grit on the granite slabs midway up the couloir combined with the fall potential there. Not my favorite of slog chutes to climb.',NULL),(184,'155564','','/u-notch-chimney-variation/155564','/u-notch-chimney-variation/climbers-log/155564/d-106685#106685','Jun 20, 2010','Night time descent','Success!','June 20th, 2010 - The last peak of a very long day as Steph and I made a good effort at a Palisade traverse. We descended the E Couloir of the U-Notch in the dark. Good solid neve all the way down, and some frightening rockfall. Luckily the bergschrund rapp station is in a protected spot!',NULL),(185,'160630','','/clyde-variation/160630','/clyde-variation/climbers-log/160630/d-106684#106684','Sep 30, 2005','Good descent route if you don\'t rapp into the','Success!','September 30, 2005 - Ascended via the U-Notch/West Chute with fresh snow in the chimney! Our rope was too short to rappel, so we descended Clyde\'s Variation. This route was easy to find on the descent, and the class 4 section was very short and solid. Exposure wasn\'t too bad.',NULL),(186,'157706','','/west-chute-u-notch-southwest-side/157706','/west-chute-u-notch-southwest-side/climbers-log/157706/d-106683#106683','Sep 30, 2005','Just as good the second time','Success!','September 30, 2005 - Ascended via the U-Notch/West Chute with fresh snow in the chimney! Leading that pitch was cold and snowy as spindrift kept blowing up the E Couloir of the U-Notch. Our rope was too short to rappel, so we descended Clyde\'s Variation.',NULL),(187,'155706','','/from-the-u-notch/155706','/from-the-u-notch/climbers-log/155706/d-106682#106682','Sep 20, 2003','Linked with N Pal','Success!','Nice summit. I had an excellent view of the class 4 descent on Sill that Dirk and I had downclimbed in the dark earlier in the month. The climb from the U-notch was shorter than the Chimney variation to North Palisade, but it was definitely more difficult!',NULL),(188,'378567','','/thunderbolt-to-sill-traverse/378567','/thunderbolt-to-sill-traverse/climbers-log/378567/d-106652#106652','Jun 20, 2010','Asterisk','No','Almost there! Steph Abegg and I climbed the North Couloir of Thunderbolt and made it to the U-Notch in time for sunset (my bad on the excessive simul-climbing and hacking cough of death. Sorry!). From there we decided to bail down to the Palisade Glacier.',NULL),(189,'157074','','/traverse-from-thunderbolt/157074','/traverse-from-thunderbolt/climbers-log/157074/d-106650#106650','Jun 20, 2010','More straightforward?','Success!','than getting to Thunderbolt from the N Couloir, or the final section to North Pal!',NULL),(190,'157968','','/east-ridge/157968','/east-ridge/climbers-log/157968/d-105248#105248','','Good Regular Route','Success!','May, 2002 - Great day hike. Hiked from 10 am \'till 3 pm. Celebrated w/ some brewskis with fellow Wasatch Mountain Club hikers. One of my favorite hikes. I\'ve gotta try this peak in the winter. I also have ambitions to do it again as part of the Beatout Ridgerun.',NULL),(191,'157850','','/swan-slab/157850','/swan-slab/climbers-log/157850/d-104767#104767','May 7, 2010','First Climb &amp; Lead in Yosemite Valley','Success!','Routes Climbed',NULL),(192,'342608','','/pine-line/342608','/pine-line/climbers-log/342608/d-104766#104766','May 8, 2010','First Time on El Cap','Success!','My first 5.7 lead in the Valley, and my 3rd overall in the Valley. Fun climb with incredible views of El Cap above.',NULL),(193,'157170','','/green-butte-ridge/157170','/green-butte-ridge/climbers-log/157170/d-102212#102212','Feb 15, 2010','Back for Revenge!','Success!','I made it to the Sargents/Green Butte junction in January, but low snow made the route too slow-going and technical to continue. This time we had better snow, but a low start (road closure was at 5,000 ft!) This made for a long day between the approach, trail breaking in soft snow from Bunny Flat, route finding difficulties through the cliffs, and my partner\'s \'tweaked\' leg acting up near the end of the route and really slowing our descent. All in all it was 26 hrs car-to-car, 22.5 miles &amp; 9,400\' of gain done on 800 calories of food. Next time I\'ll bring more snacks for this route!',NULL),(194,'156218','','/crescent-moon-couloir/156218','/crescent-moon-couloir/climbers-log/156218/d-100135#100135','Mar 20, 2004','Greatest Snow Chute Climb Ever!','Success!','A short approach, consistently steep climb, a thrilling topout, and some fun scrambling to boot - and back to the car early enough for an early dinner and drive home :-)',NULL),(195,'155708','','/northeast-face/155708','/northeast-face/climbers-log/155708/d-96567#96567','Sep 26, 2009','Perfect Day','Success!','Dayhike via the NE Face route with 3 others. We caught alpenglow views from Finger Lake, and we never saw a single cloud the entire day. No one else was on the route, and there was negligible wind on the summit. AND we were back down in time for dinner and beer.',NULL),(196,'158716','','/south-slope-via-royce-merriam-saddle/158716','/south-slope-via-royce-merriam-saddle/climbers-log/158716/d-95673#95673','Sep 12, 2009','Nice Dayhike','Success!','Dayhiked the peak via Merriam Saddle, but bailed on Merriam due to thunderstorms. A chill 12 hrs car-to-car.  Which bump was the summit?',NULL),(197,'157984','','/standard-route/157984','/standard-route/climbers-log/157984/d-94843#94843','Aug 28, 2009','Nice Easy Peak','Success!','Hiked from TH to summit via the standard trail over Flat Top\'s summit (1:30 hrs). Couldn\'t tell where Flat Top\'s summit actually was, so I cut off from the trail junction to climb Hallet (2-2:30), and then back across the plateau to climb Ptarmigan Pt (3:00) before descending, with a RT time of 4:20 hrs. Nice trail!',NULL),(198,'410106','','/lassen-peak-trail-southeast-ridge/410106','/lassen-peak-trail-southeast-ridge/climbers-log/410106/d-87211#87211','Apr 5, 2009','CHAOS Beginner Mountaineering Clinic','Success!','Spent two nights in the snow beneath this peak teaching some members of the Cal Hiking and Outdoor Society (CHAOS) basic winter mountaineering skills from climbing and beacon searches to snow shelter construction. We topped it off with a nice snow climb of the peak.',NULL),(199,'155538','','/casaval-ridge/155538','/casaval-ridge/climbers-log/155538/d-87208#87208','Apr 26, 2009','3rd Time\'s a Charm!','Success!','I tried to dayhike the route twice before, failing due to an oncoming cold and a freaky windslab. This time I was successful despite bruising my ribs the day before. Excellent route!',NULL),(200,'157134','','/mount-olympus-trail/157134','/mount-olympus-trail/climbers-log/157134/d-83216#83216','Jan 1, 2009','Happy New Year!','Success!','I climbed Mt Olympus with Joe and Shelley to celebrate New Years this year. I sat whimpering at the ice crux just long enough (plus my leg cramp) to miss the last ascent of the year, but I got the first of 2009 at 5 minutes past! I enjoyed watching a half-dozen firework shows in the valley, and then I spent the night on top - which I highly recommend to anyone who loves winter climbing in the Wasatch.',NULL),(201,'161508','','/hotlum-glacier/161508','/hotlum-glacier/climbers-log/161508/d-83097#83097','Sep 27, 2008','Too Late in Season, but Plenty of Fun!','No','Attempted the route from the Brewer Creek TH and made it up to the base of the 2nd icefall before reaching a dead-end from the melted out crevasses. Fun ice climbing to get there, and I can\'t wait to come back!',NULL),(202,'165318','','/three-peak-traverse/165318','/three-peak-traverse/climbers-log/165318/d-82487#82487','Jul 31, 2008','Just the North Summit','Success!','Perhaps it was because I was soloing, and out here on my bicycle on a tour from Calgary to Vancouver. Or perhaps it was the loose rock, but this summit made me nervous!',NULL),(203,'165356','','/cory-scramble/165356','/cory-scramble/climbers-log/165356/d-82483#82483','Jul 31, 2008','Scenic Scramble','Success!','This was my first ever Canadian Rockies summit. Fun scramble, and extra memorable linking it up with Mt Edith!',NULL),(204,'471705','','/goat-pass/471705','/goat-pass/climbers-log/471705/d-82481#82481','Aug 2, 2008','Interesting Descent','Success!','I kept expecting it to cliff out, but it never did! An excellent way to link Mt St Piran with Niblock and Whyte.',NULL),(205,'165478','','/st-piran-scramble/165478','/st-piran-scramble/climbers-log/165478/d-82480#82480','Aug 2, 2008','Beware the Rabid Pikas','Success!','Day 5 of my cycle tour from Calgary to Vancouver, I popped up this peak before heading over to Niblock. Beware the rabid Pikas!',NULL),(206,'155566','','/sw-ridge/155566','/sw-ridge/climbers-log/155566/d-82476#82476','Aug 6, 2008','Surpisingly solid route for the range!','Success!','The loose rock of the Canadian Rockies were leaving me pretty demoralized, but this route was a nice surprise!',NULL),(207,'163022','','/normal-route/163022','/normal-route/climbers-log/163022/d-82474#82474','Aug 9, 2008','Getting used to loose rock','Success!','Great side trip from Mt Temple with awesome views of the route. Definitely a worthwhile detour.',NULL),(208,'159690','','/west-buttress/159690','/west-buttress/climbers-log/159690/d-72983#72983','Jun 18, 2008','Buttin\' Out','Success!','Our team originally had its sights set on the West Rib, then the Upper West Rib cutoff, but ultimately we wimped out and climbed the butt. 12 hrs RT from 17k camp. I barely felt the altitude! Great weather. Trip report and photo links coming soon.',NULL),(209,'159790','','/the-trapps/159790','/the-trapps/climbers-log/159790/d-65499#65499','Oct 1, 2007','A Real Gem','Success!','I got out here climbing a bunch of weekends over the summer and fall while I was interning in New York. Crazy routes for such low ratings - and awesome climbing!',NULL),(210,'155574','','/dana-couloir/155574','/dana-couloir/climbers-log/155574/d-45519#45519','Oct 22, 2006','My first ice lead','Success!','A variety of conditions (from neve to thick brittle ice) made the climb quite interesting and fun. Being sick was not, as I was lethargic the entire day and could barely eat anything!',NULL),(211,'158310','','/se-face/158310','/se-face/climbers-log/158310/d-41964#41964','Aug 6, 2006','Sierra Challenge 2006','Success!','Climbed this peak on the 3rd day of the Sierra Challenge. Ascended via the NE Couloir (fun) and descended the SE Face (sucked) after tagging Pt Wesley. Apparently Bob Burd found a fun class 3 traverse to Mount Powell and I\'m kicking myself for not following him!',NULL),(212,'158280','','/ne-couloir/158280','/ne-couloir/climbers-log/158280/d-41963#41963','Aug 6, 2006','Sierra Challenge 2006','Success!','Climbed this peak on the 3rd day of the Sierra Challenge. Ascended via the NE Couloir (fun) and descended the SE Face (sucked) after tagging Pt Wesley. Apparently Bob Burd found a fun class 3 traverse to Mount Powell and I\'m kicking myself for not following him!',NULL),(213,'158350','','/east-face/158350','/east-face/climbers-log/158350/d-41955#41955','Aug 4, 2006','Sierra Challenge 2006 - Fun Slab Scrambling','Success!','Ascended the Central Face and descended the East Side Gulley of the East Face. I jogged about half of the approach. Very nice trail, and it was a good warm-up to Mt Florence :-D',NULL),(214,'155536','','/pole-creek-trail-seneca-lake-trail-india/155536','/pole-creek-trail-seneca-lake-trail-india/climbers-log/155536/d-41953#41953','Aug 21, 2006','A Fun Dayhike','Success!','I had a twisted plan to hike this peak in less than 24 hrs RT from the Pole Creek Trailhead and on August 21st I carried out this plan with my friend Joel Wilson. We started out extremely sleep deprived, which slowed us down, but we still managed to complete the hike in 23:36! See our trip report for more info and photos.',NULL),(215,'161336','','/zee-tree/161336','/zee-tree/climbers-log/161336/d-41952#41952','Jul 23, 2006','My first Tuolumne Lead','Success!','A fun day on the Dome. Dirk let me lead the first 3 pitches, which were quite thrilling as I am not used to the bolt spacin in Tuolumne Meadows! It started to reain near the end, and Dirk quickly finished the last 2 pitches.  A great climb.',NULL),(216,'156282','','/regular-route/156282','/regular-route/climbers-log/156282/d-39561#39561','Feb 11, 2006','A Good Consolation Prize','Success!','I climbed this peak with Matthew Holliman after bailing on a nearby technical climb. I chose the class 4 friction over the class 3 stairs on the ascent, and I was wishing that I downclimbed it too as the class 3 downclimb had me quite nervous!',NULL),(217,'161862','','/northeast-ridge-face/161862','/northeast-ridge-face/climbers-log/161862/d-36898#36898','Aug 6, 2005','Climbed','Success!','Climbed this with Bob Burds Sierra Challenge posse. A fun scramble on fairly solid rock - definitely much better than the NW Ridge!',NULL),(218,'166454','','/west-ridge/166454','/west-ridge/climbers-log/166454/d-36896#36896','Aug 7, 2005','Route Descended','Success!','Interesting climb - I wish I could have done the SE Face/Ridge w/ Bob and Glenn, but the water was too much for me. The SE chute was nice at the bottom, filled with a lot of bouldering moves, but the top 2/3 was a slog w/ a lot of branching dead ends.',NULL),(219,'157056','','/southeast-face/157056','/southeast-face/climbers-log/157056/d-36895#36895','Aug 7, 2006','Route Descended','Success!','Interesting climb - I wish I could have done the SE Face/Ridge w/ Bob and Glenn, but the water was too much for me. The SE chute was nice at the bottom, filled with a lot of bouldering moves, but the top 2/3 was a slog w/ a lot of branching dead ends.',NULL),(220,'166654','South Ridge','/south-ridge/166654','/south-ridge/climbers-log/166654/d-36894#36894','Aug 9, 2005','South Ridge','Success!','Summitted this peak w/ Bob Burd &amp; Co. on the Sierra Challenge. A fun scramble with some interesting routefinding on the approach. I climbed up and down some interesting 4th class offwidth cracks beside the class 3 variation leading to the summit block from the south.',NULL),(221,'165874','Contact Crack','/contact-pass/165874','/contact-pass/climbers-log/165874/d-36893#36893','Aug 11, 2005','Contact Crack','Success!','Climbed this as part of the Sierra Challenge. I almost wimped out on the final exposed class 2 traverse to the summit (after free-soloing the 5.2 Contact Crack!), but luckily Matthew was able to lure me over by dangling a runner near me as I scrambled the the rest of the way :-D',NULL),(222,'157716','Pioneer Route','/pioneer-route/157716','/pioneer-route/climbers-log/157716/d-36892#36892','Sep 3, 2005','Pioneer Route','Success!','Climbed this awesome spire with Dirk on an extended trip to OR to climb the 3 Sisters. I expected that I could just jug up the aid pitch, but instead I had to learn how to aid climb on the spot (and in the dark) to clean the pitch! I never realized how exausting aid climbing was until then :-)',NULL),(223,'157970','Harrington Couloir','/harrington-couloir/157970','/harrington-couloir/climbers-log/157970/d-36890#36890','Sep 25, 2005','Harrington Couloir','Success!','fun climb, good friends, and sunny weather. What more could one ask for?!',NULL),(224,'157002','North Couloir','/north-couloir/157002','/north-couloir/climbers-log/157002/d-36891#36891','Sep 24, 2005','North Couloir','Success!','Fun climb, although the ice wasn\'t \'in\' yet - just a smattering if ice beneath very cruddy and irregular neve. Harrington Couloir on Mt Thompson was in much better condition. The climb at the top was fun - the 5.6 variation was fun, although very short.',NULL),(225,'160454','North West Ridge','/north-west-ridge/160454','/north-west-ridge/climbers-log/160454/d-36889#36889','Mar 13, 2004','North West Ridge','Success!','Great climb! Hiked up to the end of the Chaos Crags the first night. Climbed the peak saturday via a slighlty different route than the planned north ridge. Steep snow, wild terrain! The summit bowl was great too, although I could have done without the giant metal dildo on the higher south summit.',NULL),(226,'155800','SW Ridge via Collier Glacier','/southwest-ridge-via-collier-glacier/155800','/southwest-ridge-via-collier-glacier/climbers-log/155800/d-36888#36888','Sep 5, 2005','SW Ridge via Collier Glacier','Success!','A beatiful climb, although the route done w/o snow leaves something to be desired - I pray to god I never get on rock that loose ever again! It was interesting watching breezes set off rockfall on the Terrible Traverse. The Bowling Alley was actually really fun, with relatively solid rock (which got more solid as the scrambling got more difficult).',NULL),(227,'155670','','/disappointment-cleaver/155670','/disappointment-cleaver/climbers-log/155670/d-36815#36815','May 20, 2006','More Interesting Than I Expected','Success!','Getting onto the DC was much more exposed and tenuous than I had expected - for me I\'d say it was the highlight of the route.',NULL),(228,'163146','','/west-face-via-bells-canyon/163146','/west-face-via-bells-canyon/climbers-log/163146/d-34904#34904','Jul 11, 2004','An outing with the Wasatch Mtn Club','Success!','Climbed N Thunder Mtn first by cutting over to Thunder Mtn Bowl from the upper reservoir. I then followed the ridgeline (class 3, with some exposure) to S Thunder before descending Bells Canyon. Both summits had very nice registers on top.',NULL),(229,'163144','','/coalpit-gulch/163144','/coalpit-gulch/climbers-log/163144/d-34903#34903','Oct 16, 2004','The start of a good circuit','Success!','I climbed this route with Joe Bullough before continuing on to S Thunder, Big Horn Pk, and Lone Peak for a good day out!',NULL),(230,'164670','','/bouissonier/164670','/bouissonier/climbers-log/164670/d-34902#34902','Mar 25, 2006','My first route at Joshua Tree','Success!','The weather was too bad for our attempt of the NE Ridge of Mt Williamson, so Vlad, Joel, and I headed out to JT. This was my first time to JT and Bouissonier was the first route that I climbed. Truly a fun route! It also provided good opportunities to TR the routes to the right, which allowed us to climb by headlamp well after sunset :-D',NULL),(231,'167674','','/overhang-bypass/167674','/overhang-bypass/climbers-log/167674/d-34899#34899','Mar 27, 2006','My Largest Overhang Yet','Success!','Really fun climb. Thanks for the great lead, Vlad!',NULL),(232,'154313','See Below','/little-cottonwood-canyon/154313','/little-cottonwood-canyon/climbers-log/154313/d-23063#23063','1999 - Present','Route Climbed: See Below Date Climbed: 1999 -','Success!','Routes Led:\rLisa Falls - Lisa Falls Right (5.5), Neurotica (5.5), Flee Flicker (5.7+)\rSchool Room - Chicken Chickenhead (3/4, couldn\'t protect the rest, I shall return!)(5.6), Bushwack Crack (1st 15 ft, I shall return!)(5.8)\r\rOther Routes Climbed:\rLisa Falls - Lefty (5.4), Safety Blitz (5.7), Lisa Falls Left (5.8 R), Sweet Spot (5.8+ R), Drag Queen (5.8+), Fleeting Glimpse (5.8+), Hard Knocks (5.9+), Sweep Left (5.10b)\rFive Fingers Area - Fat Man\'s Misery (5.5)\rCrescent Crack Buttress - The Ross Connection (Pitch 1, 5.8), Crescent Crack (Pitch 1, 5.7)\rPrune Face - Shuffleboard (5.8), Prune Face (5.9)',NULL),(233,'154148','See Below','/big-cottonwood-canyon/154148','/big-cottonwood-canyon/climbers-log/154148/d-21549#21549','1999-Present','Route Climbed: See Below Date Climbed: 1999-P','Success!','Routes Led:\rStorm Mountain Island - Layback Crack (5.5), Six Pence (5.6), The Flake (5.5), Epic Wall (5.5)\rStatic Wall - Reservoir Ridge (5.4)\rSalt Lake Slips - Italian Arete (5.6)\r\rOther Routes Climbed:\rNarcolepsy Wall - Narcosis (5.8), Turn of the Sentry (5.8), Narcolepsy (5.8 R), Suture Fancy (5.9), Dreamscape (5.9+), Involuntary Release (5.10a)\rStorm Mountain Island - Six Appeal (5.6)\rStatic Wall - Transformer (5.8)\rBumble Bee Wall - Fowl Play (5.9+)\rSalt Lake Slips - Entre Nous (5.8+), Thieving Magpie (5.7), Roll the Bones (5.6)\rDogwood Crag - A Modest Man from Mandrake (5.9), Take Me to the River (5.7)\rJHCOB Wall - Outside Corner (5.7)\rDead Snag - Steort\'s Ridge (5.6)\rMill B - The Extrusion (5.3)',NULL);
